{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17524073","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17524073"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:01:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:01:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13973"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13973","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13973"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.36,0.15,0.42,0.03,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6607"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50030"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6607","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6607"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13973"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35281"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"517"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"3457"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13366"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13367"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13864"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39126"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43925"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50030","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/50030"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 64-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a three-month history of worsening epigastric pain, nausea, and vomiting. He reports early satiety and has lost 8 kg over this period. He has a medical history of rheumatoid arthritis. His medications include methotrexate and meloxicam. On examination, he appears dehydrated with a pulse rate of 100/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Abdominal examination reveals epigastric tenderness and a succussion splash. A CT scan of the abdomen is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of this patient\u0027s presenting condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pancreatic cancer","Bezoar","Peptic stricture","Crohn\u0027s disease","Gallstone ileus"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation and the imaging findings in this case are consistent with gastric outlet obstruction (GOO) due to a \u003Cstrong\u003Epeptic stricture\u003C/strong\u003E. The patient\u0027s chronic epigastric pain, postprandial vomiting, weight loss, and the CT image showing a dilated stomach all support this diagnosis. The use of meloxicam, a non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drug (NSAID), is a risk factor for peptic ulcer disease, which can lead to stricture formation. The main aetilogy of gastric outlet obstruction is changing now towards malignancy since the introduction of proton pump ihibitors and the eradication of H.pylori infections, however this patient has strong risk factors for peptic stricturing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPancreatic cancer\u003C/strong\u003E can cause GOO by external compression of the duodenum, but it typically presents in older individuals and is often associated with jaundice, which is not mentioned in this case. The CT image does not show any pancreatic mass.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ebezoar\u003C/strong\u003E is a mass of undigested material in the gastrointestinal tract, which can cause obstruction. However, bezoars are typically associated with risk factors such as previous gastric surgery, psychiatric disorders, or excessive consumption of high-fiber foods, none of which are mentioned in this patient\u0027s history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECrohn\u0027s disease\u003C/strong\u003E can cause strictures in the small bowel, but it rarely affects the proximal duodenum to cause GOO. Additionally, Crohn\u0027s disease typically presents with chronic diarrhea, abdominal pain, and other systemic symptoms, which are not present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGallstone ileus\u003C/strong\u003E can cause bowel obstruction, but it typically affects the distal small bowel rather than the proximal duodenum. It is also usually an acute presentation rather than the chronic symptoms described here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPeptic ulcer disease can lead to scarring and stricture formation, particularly at the pylorus or proximal duodenum. This patient\u0027s use of NSAIDs, which are known to increase the risk of peptic ulcer disease, likely contributed to the development of a peptic stricture, causing his current presentation of gastric outlet obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Gastric outlet obstruction can be caused by peptic ulcer disease, leading to stricture formation at the pylorus or proximal duodenum.","Chronic epigastric pain, postprandial vomiting, and weight loss are characteristic symptoms of gastric outlet obstruction.","CT imaging in gastric outlet obstruction typically shows a dilated stomach with little to no contrast passing into the duodenum."],"references":["Jeong SJ, Lee J. Management of gastric outlet obstruction: Focusing on endoscopic approach. World J Gastrointest Pharmacol Ther. 2020 Jun 9;11(2):8-16. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7288729/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35281"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13973"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20866"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20866","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20866"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/mE6GTxwhlMSJM3i1JP0DwJI6Em7SXX.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/mE6GTxwhlMSJM3i1JP0DwJI6Em7SXX.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":495,"height":495}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35281","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/35281"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-05T21:34:01+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-05T21:34:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6607"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50030"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"517","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/517"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Gastric outlet obstruction","synonyms":[